class Solution {
    public int maxSubstrings(String word) {
        int count = 0;
        int n = word.length();
        int lastSeenIndex[] = new int[26];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            char c = word.charAt(i);
            int idx = c - 'a';
            if (i - lastSeenIndex[idx] >= 4) {
                count++;
            }
            lastSeenIndex[idx] = i;
        }
        return count;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates over the string once, maintaining a record of the last seen index for each character. It increments the count whenever it encounters a character that is at least 4 positions away from its last seen index, effectively counting non-intersecting substrings that start and end with the same character.
